  "text": "Prometheus enforces TLS and authentication for remote write endpoints through a comprehensive multi-layered system:\n\n## Configuration and Validation\n\nThe primary configuration structures are defined in `config/config.go`:\n\n1. **RemoteWriteConfig** (line 1419): Contains all remote write configuration including HTTPClientConfig which embeds TLS configuration, basic auth, bearer tokens, and other auth mechanisms. The `UnmarshalYAML` method (line 1448) validates configuration by calling:\n   - `c.HTTPClientConfig.Validate()` - validates TLS and standard HTTP client config\n   - `validateAuthConfigs(c)` - ensures only one auth method is configured\n   - `validateHeaders(c.Headers)` - prevents direct authorization header manipulation\n\n2. **validateAuthConfigs** (line 1491): A critical validation function that ensures at most one of the following can be configured:\n   - basic_auth (HTTPClientConfig.BasicAuth)\n   - authorization (HTTPClientConfig.Authorization with Bearer tokens)\n   - oauth2 (HTTPClientConfig.OAuth2)\n   - sigv4 (SigV4Config)\n   - azuread (AzureADConfig)\n   - google_iam (GoogleIAMConfig)\n\n3. **validateHeaders** (line 1529): Validates that the authorization header is not directly set in custom headers, forcing users to use the proper auth configuration mechanisms.\n\n4. **RemoteReadConfig** (line 1587): Similar structure to RemoteWriteConfig with HTTPClientConfig validation through `UnmarshalYAML` (line 1613).\n\n## Client Creation with TLS/Auth Enforcement\n\nThe `storage/remote/client.go` file implements client creation:\n\n1. **NewWriteClient** (line 183): Creates HTTP clients for remote write with the following authentication layers:\n   - Uses `config_util.NewClientFromConfig()` with HTTPClientConfig which handles TLS configuration and standard auth\n   - Applies SigV4RoundTripper for AWS Signature Version 4\n   - Applies AzureADRoundTripper for Azure AD authentication\n   - Applies GoogleIAM RoundTripper for Google Cloud authentication\n   - Injects custom headers via InjectHeadersRoundTripper\n\n2. **NewReadClient** (line 151): Similar to NewWriteClient but for remote read operations, also using HTTPClientConfig validation.\n\n3. **ClientConfig** (line 128): Contains configuration for both read and write clients including HTTPClientConfig which encapsulates TLS settings.\n\n## Bearer Token Authentication\n\nThe `storage/remote/azuread/azuread.go` file implements Azure AD authentication:\n\n1. **AzureADConfig** (line 91): Configuration structure with validation in `Validate()` method (line 131) that ensures:\n   - Cloud is properly specified\n   - Exactly one authentication method is configured\n   - IDs and tokens have valid format\n\n2. **NewAzureADRoundTripper** (line 237): Creates a round tripper that injects Bearer token authorization:\n   - Retrieves access tokens from Azure credential sources\n   - Sets Authorization header with \"Bearer <token>\" pattern (line 265-266)\n\n## Google IAM Authentication\n\nThe `storage/remote/googleiam/googleiam.go` file provides Google Cloud authentication:\n\n1. **NewRoundTripper** (line 34): Creates authentication round tripper that:\n   - Uses Google Cloud credentials (from file or default credentials)\n   - Adds proper authorization headers for monitoring.write scope\n\n## Integration Points\n\n1. **WriteStorage.ApplyConfig** in `storage/remote/write.go` (line 139):\n   - Processes RemoteWriteConfig from main config\n   - Creates NewWriteClient with HTTPClientConfig, SigV4Config, AzureADConfig, GoogleIAMConfig\n   - Ensures TLS/auth validation happens during client creation\n\n2. **Storage.ApplyConfig** in `storage/remote/storage.go` (line 90):\n   - Processes RemoteReadConfig\n   - Creates NewReadClient ensuring remote read endpoints also have proper TLS/auth\n\nThe architecture ensures that TLS configuration is validated through the HTTPClientConfig.Validate() method (from prometheus/common), basic authentication and bearer tokens are handled through the HTTPClientConfig structure, and advanced authentication methods (SigV4, Azure AD, Google IAM) are applied via composable round trippers, all with mutual exclusivity validation to prevent configuration conflicts."
}

